title: Professional grade drone at beginner/toy price!
text:
I've owned five drones and I'm extremely impressed by this drone over all the others.

The pictures I've attached are taking off at maybe 30m, view looking straight down from about 100m high during daylight, and skyline at night at about 120m (max height allowable by FAA). Do note it was pretty windy up at 120m the night I took that picture. These are just the ones that were sent to my phone; pictures saved to the SD card are of higher quality.

Pros: Outstanding power - this drone can fight, and win, against light and moderate wind! The app even tells you when the wind conditions are getting dangerous for flight! Well done.
Folding profile and carrying case is extremely well done - over and beyond convenient. Folding arms snap into place, so they aren't going to jostle out of alignment during flight. Case is soft yet protective; no trouble fitting it in a backpack and hiking along with it.
ABS plastic + reinforced aluminum frame means this thing is durable and built to last.
Using the 5GHz wireless signal and my phone I've gotten steady real time video transmission from over 300m away and 120m high, consistently, without losing connection. That's impressive at this price point!
Return to home/GPS is ALWAYS spot on; you can count on this drone coming back exactly to you! Major plus.
This really does fly for up to 30 minutes as advertised. This will of course depend on wind, speed setting, and how aggressively you're flying it though, so your flight time will be influenced by your conditions and flight pattern.
Extremely responsive controls, and steady enough flight to get quality pictures and video. Three speed modes; I like to put it on the lowest speed setting once it gets close to the ground for landing, or when I'm steadying it to take a picture relatively close up. Putting it on max speed and racing it around is a blast too.
This drone uses 5GHz band to connect with your phone wirelessly. This is good; better video quality and better signal transmission means you can communicate with it from further distances without being crowded by numerous 2.4GHz signals usually in any given area these days. You want this over 2.4GHz for a wireless connection to your phone. (Of course the pictures and video are saved to the SD card, but for maintaining a good real time image and connectivity you want the 5GHz channel.)
I really can't recommend this enough; skip the toys and get this - it's worth every dollar of the price!

Cons:
I have to nit-pick here, and there's not much to dislike. These are very minor points I include to make this review fair and unbiased.
It is loud; not at all hearing unsafe or offensive, but it is noticeable compared to a toy-grade drone. Any drone with this much power (read: not strictly a toy) is going to make some noise. It is not offensive though; you won't bother the neighbors.
The camera has a slight fish-eye effect when you're trying to look straight ahead. You can see that in the first picture I posted and the nighttime picture. Do note the camera is in-flight adjustable, so you can go from straight ahead to straight down, and all points in between, on the fly. So big plus for that. I can't knock the camera too much because it doesn't have a stabilizing gimble. That's a necessary trade to fit the profile. Plus if you're watching the ground at an angle the fish-eye effect goes away.
It can be just a bit slow to get a GPS lock. Don't be put off though; it's not difficult to obtain one, it just takes a couple extra seconds. It never loses the GPS signal once it's got it. (So you can hold it up high to get a signal quicker, then set it down for takeoff.)
You do have to register it with the FAA (it just barely meets their weight requirement for registration). Don't be put off: this process takes less than 5 minutes on their website, and there's zero waiting on paperwork. Just fill out the form and you're ready to fly immediately (register as a modeler/recreational flyer and you're good to go with no hassle).

Tips:
Disconnect your phone from any wireless networks it is auto-joining. This will ensure you maintain a video feed to your phone as you fly greater distances away.
Android users: when you connect to this wireless signal, you have to tell Android OS to keep connected even though there is no internet connectivity. This is a quirk of the Android OS, not the drone. Be sure to do this the first time you connect to the drone and you'll be fine.
To get a GPS signal quickly, calibrate the compass and the gyroscope as per the included instructions then hold the drone up off the ground while it searches for a GPS signal. You'll get the necessary 3 bars of signal much faster than sitting flat on the ground. (Also note - to unlock the motor to take off you must have 3 bars of GPS signal! If your drone motor is not unlocking for take off, this is why. Do not fly without GPS mode! You'll be thankful when your drone is auto-returning to the takeoff location from who knows where you've flown it - trust me!) Then just set it back down, unlock the motor, and take off.
On the geo-fencing feature, set the auto-return minimum height high enough to clear any trees in your immediate area. That way, when auto-returning, it will climb safely over the height of any trees between the initial location and the drone's current position. This will avoid crashing into anything on its automated return path.

Overall verdict: this has all of the features of more expensive, professional grade, drones at (if you catch it on sale as I did) an entry level/toy price point. Buy this. Grab an extra battery - you'll need it to feed your addiction! I can't imagine how fun this will be using VR glasses in first person view.

Flying is easy just takes a little getting used to. The range is better then I expected. The image is clear and so are the photos and videos. I like the return home button and the follow me option. They also give you extra rotors. The battery life is good I guess for a drone. The only thing is it does take a while for everything to charge. But they do give you 2 charging cables. I would recommend this to someone who is just starting out. As the price is good to where it's not some cheap piece of crap but it's also not a huge hit if you destroy it.

title: Awesome drone! (Edited)
text:
So I unfortunately need to update this review to reflect an issue I started to experience. I got the free battery that ruko gives out for fair reviews. Everything was working good, up until my phone updated to Android 10, after that I started to notice some odd issues. Like I couldn't get a GPS or camera lock at start, its as if the software/controller and the drone would not connected. I tested again later from another location, and after some futzing and calibrating several times I got it to lock and engage the camera. But when I took it up and started to fly I noticed the controls were all messed up. I could fly forward and back and side to side, but when I rotated and hit forward the controls would move me left or right instead of forward or back. The support person I spoke to said this was because it was in headless mode, but I didn't engage that. I even reset the drone/controller and tried it again and it did the same thing. With that I decided to trade it in. I'm reluctant to try a replacement based on that experience as it seems like the software on Android 10 note 10+ isn't ironed out. On Android 9, I didn't experience any issues, it connected and worked well. I'd be curious to know if others experienced odd things with the software on android 9 or 10.
________________________________________________________________________________________________________
This is my first drone ever and really like it so far. It's super easy to fly, practically flies on its own with a little assistance from me. I've played with the sub $50 dollar drone toys and enjoyed them, well for 6-7 minutes before needing to charge. This got tedius and boring after so much time spent charging. One of the major attractions to this drone is the battery life/flight time. I got about 25 min before it started to blink, which I'm sure I could've squeezed out that 5 min, but didn't want to risk it. It's durable, I tried flying inside and hit the couch, it crashed and I saw a small indent on one blade. So I don't recommend any indoor flight with this. Like others have stated, i think it would be the best drone if they included a collision sensor. Other than that, this is a great quality drone. I'm really liking all the more advanced features like the follow me option is great to record the family out having fun at the park. So far I have nothing but great things to say about the Ruko F11 Drone. I will continue to use it and will report here of any issues.

title: Camera motion very inconsistent
text: I bought this drone because it was written up in an article as being one of the top affordable drones for home inspections. For home inspections the camera is really important. Right out of the box the drone was easy to operate but I quickly noticed that the camera was stuck in the down position. I landed the drone and followed the trouble shooting guide and managed to get about 30 degrees of motion with the camera. Unacceptable. I called the numbers provided for technical support and only got an answering machine that said "the google subscriber is unavailable, please leave a message". It gave me no indication that I had reached Ruko. I left a message and a day later I received a call from Ruko and they promptly sent me a new replacement camera. It was easy enough to replace. When I flew the drone and tested the camera I had the full 90 degrees (up & down) of motion but it was very jerky. When I went to point the camera up or down it would get stuck about halfway down and then suddenly snap into motion which made for jerky, clunky video. To make matters worse, it would not move at all on other flights. Knowing that the camera was not gimbaled was not super important for me but with the motion of the camera being rough as it is I decided to send this back. For home inspections I don't need anything fancy but the camera needs to be smooth and reliable.

title: Very well made and so much more than I expected in this price range
text:
[[VIDEOID:761e6e011b0e8b2abc7b732575cbdafb]] I feel it's important to explain how I came to buy the F11 PRO Drone. Several weeks back I got suckered into purchasing a drone that was advertised on Facebook. It was an elaborate video about how some engineer at a big name brand company realized the company he worked for was purchasing lower valued electronics but charging a high brand name cost to cover advertising. So he left the brand name company and started his own with a few of his co-workers offering the same high quality electronics at a fraction of the cost because they aren't spending money on marketing. But I need to buy it now because this price won't last long after the word gets out about how great it is.
It looked like a lot of fun and now I had to have it. so I ordered it right after the advertisement ended. I know it was a compulsive purchase because before seeing the video I had never thought about having a drone. Whatever, I'm only human. Now I was excited to get this awesome drone in the mail. I waited and waited and waited, several weeks for it to finally arrive. I had never seen a drone before but even I could tell it seemed really light in weight and cheaply made. Trying not to deflate my excitement so quickly, I rationalized with myself thinking maybe it has to be light in order to fly. I very quickly learned that was not the case. The supposed high quality drone couldn't even get off the ground. When I contacted the seller about it. They told me to shake it up and down to get it working. OMG are you kidding me??? Long story short it never worked. After being let down by the drone scam, I did some research and found the F11 PRO on Amazon. It had great reviews and was still very reasonably priced. So I ordered it. Unlike the other bogus drone, the F11 PRO was delivered almost immediately. No waiting at all this time and no letting me down this time either. The difference between the two drones is night and day. The F11 PRO is sturdy, weighty, very well made and has so many cool functions i haven't even begun to master them all yet. In one of the pictures above you can see the two drones side by side. The little one is the cheap knock-off I got scammed into purchasing from a Facebook advertisement and the larger drone is the F11 PRO right out of the box. EVERYTHING is better on the F11 PRO than the cheap piece of crap advertised on Facebook. I was talking to a friend of mine who is also a beginner. He told me he had received the Mavic drone as a Christmas gift a year or two ago. The funny part is he's afraid to fly it because he hasn't gotten insurance for it yet. It's so expensive he feels the need to insure it before even attempting to fly it? That's just silly. The F11 has many of the same features as the Mavic and if I happen to crash it due to my limited knowledge in flying? I'll just buy another one because they're priced so I can. I don't see that happening because the GPS and other features on the F11 PRO prevent it from crashing. Even If you'r a beginner. Why spend thousands on a drone? You can get the same high quality experience and just as much fun with the F11 PRO. I promise you won't be disappointed. You don't need to research anymore or think about it anymore. Just buy it and you can thank me later.

It's been a few days since I wrote my review. Since then I've been learning more about this drone every day. It hasn't ceased to amaze me. Every person who has seen me flying this drone, said....I have to get one!! This thing flies so high it's hard to believe even when you're looking at it with your own two eyes. I've added a couple pics and a video I took with the drone. The video may be a little bumpy in some parts but that's all on me. I just turned on the video to see how it worked? I was still having fun flying it around. Zipping from one place to another, rather than paying attention to the filming. It still took some great footage. I'm looking forward to putting together some really nice photography & video shots with this drone. So there ya have it. After a few days I'm still loving it. As a matter of fact I bought another one for my wife because she was jealous of mine...LOL

title: ** Fanstastic Beginner Drone **
text:
This is my first drone. I'm not going to lie when I say shopping for your first drone isn't easy. There are so many to choose from based on price, reviews, skillset, etc. I had originally purchased the Holy Stone 270, as it's essentially the same drone but about $100 cheaper. After needing to send the first one (and the second) back to Amazon because the remote control would not hold a charge, I finally settled on the Roku F11. I was a little nervous because it's the same remote control. But lo! this one works just fine. :) I was prompted to purchase this one for an extra $100 because it comes with an extra battery as well. For a beginner user I want to be able to get up in the air as much as possible for practice. It was nice to know I had an whole extra battery and 25min for extra flight time (total, darn near close to an hour) to really play and get to know my drone.

First impressions:
1. Sturdy carry case and well protected. I like that if I'm traveling.
2. 2 batteries a huge plus
3. Sturdy drone and surprisingly heavier than I expected with the battery installed. It's not a cheaply built drone. Well made.
4. Downloading the app and setting up the drone for first flight - super simply. Less than 10 minutes.
5. The auto take off feature is really nice. One button launch and you're in the air hovering.
6. The return to home feature is a life saver for a beginner. First time using the RTH feature and the drone landed about 10" away from the launch pad. That's pretty good! Though I got the hang of the remote control pretty quick and probably could have landed the drone myself on my first time out.
7. Took some quick same footage. In the daylight, it's hard to see my phone's screen to see what the drone is seeing. But that's not an error with the drone.
8. Don't be discouraged from the photo quality on the Amazon reviews. I was really shocked at how nice and crisp the photos are. I wonder if Amazon has a rez limit. I think they look really good.

Cons:
1. My first time out, so I can't really say much at this point, but I thought the drone would do a little better in the wind. 10mph + winds today. Drone did struggle to fly against it. It worked fine, but with effort.
2. Attempted to leave the drone hover, and again, shocked it would pretty well stay in place even with the wind. Just going straight into the direction of the breeze is where it hurts the most.

One last thing, on final landing (during my first flight experience) I did forget how to have the drone auto land and I accidentally turned the drone off completely and it fell to the ground. Thank god it was already hovering about 18" from the ground when I did so. Even still, dusted off the dry dirt and the drone and propellars took no damage.

I would personally recommend anyone on a budget to purchase this drone.

title: Great for beginners and experience pilots. A great price with great features.
text: [[VIDEOID:8bcf16cb4315044080444b68ba008e1a]] Great drone for beginners and experienced this is my first drone, it is very easy to fly. I like how the controller folds up and also has a spot to hold your cell phone so you can see the video from the drone on it. I believe the video recording is 2.9 k and if you take pictures the camera is 4k. It comes with two batteries and the option to leave a review for a third battery for free. It also has headless mode which means you can go back and forth and left to right and it will be easier to control the drone in headless mode. And normal mode depending on the direction of where the camera is on the drone that would be your front and if you move around you could make it go in the wrong direction but after a few test flights you should be able to get it down very easily. I still have mine in beginner mode. I've flown it four or five times just shortly and last night is the first time I've recorded video on it. You don't have to use but I installed an SD card into the drone so every picture and video recording gets stored on board. If you don't have an SD card then everything gets stored on your phone, I actually think that it stores to your phone no matter what but the SD card might possibly always be running I'll have to check that out. it's great and once I figured out all these features which will take some time to learn them all you can do all types of things with the drone. It has follow me mode, it can circle around a location, you can set waypoints on the app on your phone so we can automatically fly to those spots that you choose and it also has hand gestures which I have not personally tried myself but I guess you can use them to start videos or to take a picture. The drone goes up almost 4000 ft although I believe you can only see the live video for 500 meters I believe the specification said. I think if you start the recording for video when you take off and you go above the 500 m it will still record for you right onto your SD card and I think that's really what the SD card option is for in case you lose the video feed on your cell phone when flying. For this price range in the quality of the video and pictures this drone is a excellent option. The only thing I wish it had that it doesn't is obstacle avoidance. But you won't find that feature on any other drone for less than $1,000. You don't really want to get it out of your line of sight anyway though just for the chance of the drone running into something that you cannot see like power lines or something else. I'm very happy with this drone. The video I have posted isn't the best. It's the first time I've used the camera and video option and it was dark out and very cold. I had the app set to beginner mode so my range was limited. I could have flown a lot higher and farther.

title: Surpisingly decent little drone
text:
This little drone surprised me at how good it is for the price. It's my first drone, and it got me interested enough in them to buy another one with better features.

Flight time is pretty good, RTH works great, distance is pretty good, and the drone is responsive.

My complaints are as follows.

The biggest complaint is that you can only connect your phone via wifi. Sometimes it takes my phone a long time to find it, or I'll have to shut the drone off and turn it back on to get it to show up, and it likes to disconnect fairly frequently. But when it's working, it works good. The option to use a cable from the remote to the phone would be wonderful, and this was one of the compelling reasons driving me to purchase another (but much more expensive) drone.

Another complaint is that sometimes if you crash or even just land, the drone thinks it's still in flight and there is no way to shut down the motors. The poor thing will sit there, sometimes on it's side or upside down, trying it's hardest to spin the propellers and there's nothing you can do about it other than stick a hand or foot or something into the spinning blades to rectify the situation.

I wish the app would remember your settings. You can turn off beginner mode and it will stay off, but every time you go to use it you will hit max distance within 10 seconds and have to stop, go into settings, and change max distance, max height, and RTH height to your preferences again.

Don't even think about flying this indoors. With GPS turned off this thing will not hover in place. It's always moving. I can fly it great outdoors very easily but I can't fly it for more than 5 seconds inside without getting a wall or something and crashing.

All in all you get a lot for the money with this thing. The photos are pretty decent and it does about everything you could ask it to do. I think the level 7 wind claims are BS, but I expected that considering some of the top recommended drones out there in this category are level 5 winds.

title: Remote controller issues?

Beyond that I love the charge capacity of the batteries, it has very stable flight, it is my first drone so I'm not pushing the limits at all but from what I've seen it's been a great first drone, besides that controller issues?

title: Great quality for the price - until it stopped recording.  Easy to fly.
text:
[[VIDEOID:a3102b41b76ad188ece21c248049c64c]] UPDATE: 2/15/20. The Ruko F11 unfortunately stopped recording and I lost some irreplaceable footage, which really upset me.

I was just inside the return window by a few days, so I returned the drone and was refunded.

THIS is important: I decided to purchase a DJI MAVIC MINI drone, which is 2.7k, and does not have all of the features of the F11, such as follow me, BUT has a gimble - which makes the video butter smooth. The BIG deal is that the lense on the DJI is such superior quality that the video image is MUCH better than the F11. Crystal clear. Quality is noteably higher, it is easier to fly and quickly and automatically calibrated the compass to GPS. Just turn it on and fly, no spinning around before flight. Range is well over 1.5 miles compared to 1/4 mile at most for the F11.

As a new drone buyer, I was sucked into the allure of 4K video, and all of the features, but now I have learned that a crappy camera that shoots 4K is worse than a high quality one in 2.7 with a gimble.

And now I don‚Äôt have to worry about losing important footage that cannot be replaced.

Spend the extra $100 (or $200 for the Fly More combo pack with 3 batteries), and go from a disposable drone with low quality everything to something that is engineered to last years, and will take professional cinematic quality videos.

I commend Ruko for trying, and I appreciate that they have copied everything from the carrying case to remote functionality - from DJI, as this helped me to fly the DJI out of the box, but this drone misses the mark in quality and reliability.

Original review:

This is my first drone, which I bought to work on a video project for a group I'm in. Video and photo quality is very good, and photos are indeed 4K!

Flying is easy, and all functions work very well. Setup order is important: Power Drone; Power remote; pair remote; turn on app; calibrate gyroscope; connect to GPS, etc.

Range is decent. Turn phone to airplane mode and this gives the best range. Trees and buildings limit range significantly. The range of the remote is much further than the WiFi range, so your phone camera feed will freeze up hundreds of feet before the remote will no longer control the drone. Return to home is a great feature, and when I have lost sight of, and my bearings to where the drone is, this brought it back to within about 2 feet of where it took off every time.

Battery life is very good, at over 20 minutes.

Overall, a great drone, and a lot of fun to fly!

title: Great potential, but nowhere near advertised performance
text:
There are many things I like about this drone. It does seem to be of good quality, and the basic controls and short-range responsiveness seem very good. The control app is also vgood, and I especially like the map display with waypoint and drone orientation features.
While I understand that it is a lower priced drone, the main thing I was willing to give up (versus one of the drones that are 2x or 3x the F11's price) is the lack of gimbal and image stabilization. It is a little shaky and image tilts with the drone body when maneuvering, as expected, so no real complaint there.
However, even at a lower price, I was still expecting something close to the range performance that it advertises. Even in fairly ideal conditions, it way under-performed on its advertised specs. Especially the live video transmission: with the drone at about 150ft/0.5m of altitude, video feed got glitchy around 150m and froze up completely in less than 200m. Far short of the advertised live video range of 500m. With live video frozen, I was able to re-orient and fly the drone back using the map display, or the Return To Home option. But if the live video transmission range falls so short, it is hard to trust the other controls and commands beyond that range. So it could be a great drone if they could improve the actual range performance, or for someone that is sure they will always want to operate with such short range needs.

title: Easy to Fly
text: [[VIDEOID:8dbb9457b07c4e27ca8de8420e2768c7]] New to the sport.  Started with a cheaper, lighter quad copter and was getting discouraged having to constantly fight with controlling one that seemed to have a mind of it's own.  The Ruko (SJRC) F11 Pro is very easy and forgiving to fly, which makes it fun instead of frustrating.  When you release the joy sticks, it stops and hovers until you make the next move, which is great for us beginners.  The drone is solid and appears very well made.  I had no trouble connecting to the app with both a Galaxy S7 and a Galaxy S9 Android phone.  I have not used a micro sd card as yet.  Without the card the photos and videos are saved to a folder created in your phone.  Still haven't experimented with the circle, follow me and way point features, but I have used the return and land feature, and it works great!  I am very well pleased with my purchase and recommend it to other beginners like myself.

text: [[VIDEOID:343b82a3b87c2c0cfd8e1ed1d8a2d9c7]] This is a great drone the won't break the bank for beginners and experienced  fliers. This is my second drone I have owned.  A couple years ago I purchased a little toy drone to learn the basics and recently decided to step up my game and boy am I glad I did. This is easy to set up and fly. It seems to do very well in the lower winds and being that it weighs a bit over 1lb helps. I am very impressed with this so far and would recommend it.

title: Awesome Drone, Excellent Customer Service
text:
I've only had mine for a few days but so far this thing performs great. I've had no problems with the video to my phone although I haven't gone a great distance yet. It was very easy to set up and as far as ease of control this thing is unbelievable. It's not fast, at least in beginner mode. I haven't taken it out of beginner mode yet. If you're going full speed forward or side to side and you let go of the sticks, the drone comes to a hover. The flight times are as advertised. I got 30 minutes out of both batteries on my first flight and I don't think they were even fully charged. My next few flights we're just as good on time. So far the video seems as good as they claim and I haven't used the memory slot video. It's supposed to be a lot better. I haven't noticed a lot of shaking going on in the video. The servo that moves my camera is always buzzing which, in my experience, means it's under some sort of stress. I'll update after I've used the "follow me" and "waypoints" part of the app but so far I am very pleased and the drone itself is powerful and can handle the wind.
UPDATE: I was having an issue with my camera so they were going to send me a new one. They sent me a video on how to switch out the camera but when I was removing the camera, 2 micro wifi board connectors popped off the wires. I talk customer support and ask them to send me a couple of new connectors but they didn't have any so they replace my drone with a new one. This is the best customer service I have ever dealt with. They respond to your emails quickly and are ready to help in any way they can. I love this company and I love this drone. Highly recommend for beginners and mid-range drone pilots. If you're looking to do some aerial photography then I would also recommend this drone. It may not have a gimbal but you can line up your shots intake great photographs. Especially the ones on the memory card. This is a great deal and I always get it while you can.

title: Great Customer Service
text:
I will divide this review into several different parts. Part One: Flight. The F11 flies well enough for the price. It‚Äôs responsive. It tends to over react when you end a maneuver. This does not bode well if you are taking a video. Part Two: Remote. This remote is very basic. The remote on the HS 720 is a much better remote providing a lot more information. Part Three: Smartphone Display. The WiFi signal between the F11 and my iPhone is weak at best. I only get video displayed out to about 300 yards. After that the WiFi signal drops out and the on screen video freezes. Very disappointing. Part Five: Camera. The camera is ok. I don‚Äôt like the built in down angle on the lens so you don‚Äôt see the blades. It can make judging the height of obstacles in front of you hard to judge. It also has a hard time adapting to light changes. A him left mount would be helpful. Overall I give it about 3.8 out of five stars. Give it a stronger WiFi signal, software upgrade and fix the camera and it would be a solid 5 star.
New update on this drone. Nearing the end of my flight yesterday, I enabled the RTH feature on my drone. After what seemed like a really long period of time, my drone finally appeared overhead. The drone never stabilized to a hover, but instead was flying erratically. I tried to regain control but could not. The drone would take off in one direction and then change course to another. I could control the altitude and the direction, but as soon as I tried to hover it, off it would go. I had good GPS signal the whole time. Finally crashed into the woods bout 100 meters from me after the battery died. Only plus note was the tracking feature on the app enabled me to find my drone in the woods. Result, right front arm broken and several props damaged. I do not recommend this drone anymore and would not by it again.
Well the saga continues. Contacted Ruko again. They sent me a refurbished drone. Have been flying that one with great success. Even though I have had some problems with their drones, they do provide great customer service and they make it right. I am aware that this happens to just about every manufacturer that I have looked into. I think drone manufactures are trying to develop their drones features to quickly and maybe not testing the environments they fly in. But customer service is the key and Ruko comes thru in spades.

title: Drone malfunctioned and went off into a tree with less than 3 months use.
text:
[[VIDEOID:477ea69d12c189d41ac474481148f237]] I would have given this drone a great review because it was good while we had it, but on my husband's last flight in November 15th the drone malfunctioned and would not allow him to gain control while it was suspended in the air. The drone lost its control and went off into a tree and we were unable to recover it. I contacted the seller on this issue and I am having a difficult time trying to get any resolution on this issue. The product was still within 3 months of receiving it. We followed the instructions to send over flight data but the app is not working as the instruction specified. We sent the last video recording which clearly shows it was malfunctioning and a screen recording of how the app is not responding. I would be lying if I said I wasn't frustrated because to spend this kind of money for something to last less than 3 months just feels like a waste of money and upsetting to be honest. I am hoping to receive some positive responses from the seller.

I will update my review once I am able to have this issue cleared. Just be mindful of your purchases.

title: I Love my New Drone
text:
[[VIDEOID:be6d93fba16d4f83bac0a392a02214ba]] After much research, I finally settled on the Ruko F11 Pro 4K. Today was my maiden flight and I must say that I am very happy with my purchase. It‚Äôs hard to believe that a drone of this caliber and quality costs only 300.00. The pros for me are as follows:
1. Price- I thought it was very reasonable considering what‚Äôs in the box.
2. Remote control- Unit is very easy to use and setup was a breeze. Drone was very responsive
3. The F11- Drone was easy to calibrate, fly, and store
4. Battery life- I got 22-24 minutes out of the 30 minute rated battery. I think I can get more but I didn‚Äôt want to push it.
5. Camera- The camera took great videos of my neighborhood and the footage was very smooth, not jerky. It literally made me look like a seasoned flyer instead of a first time one
6. Aesthetics- The look is badass, no need to say more
7. App features- The app is packed with features. I didn‚Äôt test them all but was satisfied with the waypoint feature, one touch takeoff and land, and follow me mode.

Cons- For me, I don‚Äôt have any, I absolutely love this drone and am looking forward to many hours of fun! Thanks Ruko! For building a great drone!

What's the point if you can only fly 15 minutes at a time. By the time you get used to the drone, times up, dead battery. This one goes for 25+ minutes and comes with 2 batteries. text:
I picked up this drone because of the price and the high amount of positive feedback. It's clear it was a good choice. First thing you notice is the nice case. Everything fits very nicely into it's cut foam area to keep it very snug and safe during transporting. Then you notice the solid build of the drone and the weight. Not overly heavy but you know you can fly it outside and not worry about a breeze blowing it away. Because of the weight it will need to be registered with the FAA but that was only 5 minutes and $5 for a three years. Next you notice how easy it is to change the battery. This is great as I've had some drones you nearly had to do surgery on to get to the charge port on the battery. Then there is the flight. I've only had it out for it's maiden flight but talk about impressed. I hooked the remote up to my Samsung Galaxy Note 9. The instructions to get the drone up and flying were very easy to follow. Then it was up. The drone starts in "beginner" mode so won't go as high or as far. This is good so you can get used to it but can easily change it and set your own height and distance limits. Very smooth controls and response from the drone. No jerkiness. Took it up, flew it around. Pivoted the camera remotely. (great feature) then took it as high and far as I could in the beginner mode and hit the auto return/land. It put it right down less than a foot from where it took off. GPS worked great on it. This being my first flight and spending extra time getting used to the features of the App and remote, I spent all of 20-25 minutes on this flight on the one battery.
Overall I'm very impressed with this drone and very I chose this one over all the other drone choices.
For the money, I don't feel you could find a better drone.

title: Great product for first time user.  Instructions could be improved.
text:
I love my purchase but I had to spend a lot of time watching third party youtube videos and ultimately sitting down and making my own cheat sheet to use while I was learning the system. I would love to see a laminated quick guide with launching steps on one side and flying/control diagram on the other.

The unit itself is well made and feature rich. I recommend keeping things simple to start:

1. Go thru launch sequence a few time perhaps just launching and landing. Make sure wide open field and lite to no wind.
2. Move on to make sure all the functions are calibrated and working such as GPS, gimble, etc. the drone should be able to hover with not intervention from controls.
3. Next try the manual flying with something simple. Don‚Äôt panic most corrections can be made by releasing the controller and allowing drone to return to hover.
4. Test and fully learn the return to home function
5. Test and fully learn the emergency landing function
6. Try the automated flight function (creating a flight way points)
7. Play around with video and picture taking
8. Play around with follow me function

Now you have the basics. And for the advanced you can go after facial/person recognition follow function or hand gesture functions. I have yet to cross that line.

VERY COOL PURCHASE AND TRULY RECOMMEND.

title: GREAT Drone Value
text:
This is my 1st drone. I'm 71 yrs old, retired and have been flying RC planes for many decades, but never a copter.

PROS - The F11 Pro is VERY stout, simple to use, has terrific flight times, is super steady in the hover and really could NOT be easier to safely fly while having great fun. The camera provides a great picture and the operational range and the speed of this drone once out of "Beginner" flight parameters is simply amazing. But in Beginner mode I am certain anyone can fly it and learn to fly it well. It comes with two flight batteries which many drone packages do not offer. The carry case is good looking, fits the components perfectly and provides very good protection. I feel the F11 Pro is a good starter drone and still maintains being an "adult" drone with NO toy-like sie or features.

CONS - The transmitter's fake antennas serve no purpose at all and are rather silly IMHO - the real antenna is inside the transmitter on a circuit board. The smart phone holder is rather 'flimsy' and the top & bottom "lips" of the holder cannot grasp my Moto G6 Play very well if I leave it in its protective case. If the edges were only slightly deeper and the spring slider more robust it would be a a true treat.

Other than those two admittedly 'picky' negatives, I think this unit represents a solid value at a reasonably price. Get one, you won't be disappointed.

text:

title: Great drone for the price
text:
I was impressed with this drone. Ruko packed a lot of features into a small drone for this price and they all work fairly well. I think just about anyone could fly this drone with minimal instruction.

Pros

Great battery life
Follow-Me
GPS auto-navigation
Good video quality

Cons
There is a rudimentary gimble that only moves along the Y axis. If you need video that isn't jerky, invest a little bit more and get a drone with a camera stabilization gimble.

Feature request.

It would be great if Ruko developed a simple app that could be used with GPS and wifi-enabled smart watches like Samsung and Apple watches. This would allow the drone to follow someone who is performing activities like surfing or running.

title: Amazing Technology
text:
The only prior drone experience I have is a battery helicopter from about 10 years ago. What a difference. This Ruko F11 drone is amazing. There is a bit of a learning curve, but nothing compared to years ago. If you take your hands off the controls, it just hovers in place and stays within about a 3 foot sphere. The camera works well. Yes, it comes with two batteries with the option for a possible third if you "write honest product review" on Amazon. The batteries last about 25-30 minutes as advertised.
When I first started (without fully reading the directions) I crashed it into the furniture three times and it seems no worse for the ware. It has solid high-grade plastic construction. Motors are relatively quiet.
This thing essentially has an inertial navigation system paired with GPS. Did I mention that it is Amazing?
In a 5-8 mph wind it does fine. On a moderately windy day I moved it up to about 200 feet where there was a stronger wind and I had to bring it back down to maintain control.
I don't know what the other recent generation drones are like, but this one is well worth a few hundred dollars.

title: Great drone, Worth it for the price. Great for beginners and Intermediate/advanced
text:
I don‚Äôt normally write reviews but I was surprised by the drone quality for the price that it is. This is my first real drone I‚Äôve purchased. (I have other RC type drones that are much cheaper in function and price) I did do a good amount of research on drones before purchasing. I believe this is a great drone for beginners and for the intermediate/advanced. Especially for the price.

In depth Review below...

Follow the directions. Read/skim through the short manual it comes with. The later pages are the most important on the functions and operating, charging etc. Theres also good videos on YouTube you can watch as well since the manual and video they provide is not the clearest of explanations. The drone is in beginner mode by default so it won‚Äôt go that far or high until you override the settings but it‚Äôs great for a beginner like myself to get used to. For my first few times using it I made sure to use it in a wide open space but it‚Äôs easy to get the hang of and feel comfortable with controlling it. After 2-3 uses i was comfortable enough to increase the flight height and distance in the settings in the app. You can also change the speed setting from the controller and the angle of the camera which is great.

I don‚Äôt really have any negatives to say except that I think it‚Äôs crazy it takes 5 hours to charge the battery for 20-30 minutes of flight time (depending on conditions/flight speed/movement) But thats not specific to this drone it‚Äôs just normal average flight time with drone batteries. Also this comes with 2 batteries so it makes up for the short flight time.

I‚Äôve flown the drone 5-6 times now and once at night. I‚Äôve used the Take-Off/Landing button/function which works well. The Return Home one is great as well especially if the drone gets out of your sight and you lose your sense of direction in regards to the location of the drone and the take off point. Just be aware that when in Return Home mode the drone does not avoid obstacles such as trees. But I did see a Return Altitude setting with the Height and Distance settings so I think as long as you set this high enough (above the trees) you can have the drone ‚ÄúReturn Home‚Äù to above you then safely land it manually. I haven‚Äôt played with the rest of the functions like Follow-Me mode, Point of Interest, Way Point Flight or the Hand Gesture function. I just don‚Äôt have any use for those functions at the moment or the right environment to test them but I will update here once I test out the rest of the functions/modes. But that being said there‚Äôs a bunch of functionality. I think the drone is worth it even with out having tested all the other functions yet. Its easy to use and control. The camera quality is pretty darn good. I would recommend this drone for anyone whose looking for a quality drone for a good price.

title: Easy to learn, fun to fly, good quality video, durable.
text:
I waited to write a review until I'd gotten to fully test all the features, and the verdict is I'm really enjoying this drone! It's a huge step up from the little $60 micro indoor drone I'd been using previously.

The GPS stabilization is great with light wind, and makes learning feel safer. You can just let go of the controls and know that it'll stay in place, or press return to home if it gets out of sight and you panic. The video transmission is clear, and I felt comfortable flying solely by looking at the camera stream in quick time. The follow-me, orbit, and point-of-interest guided flight functions all work well.

It's also durable. I crashed it once while flying indoors, and it fell from about 9-10 ft with no major side-effects - just a few scuffs on two of the blades.

The instructions and the video that they offer to teach you how to use drone are good, but there are also many helpful videos on youtube to get the hang of any functions you're struggling with.

All in all, I'd recommend the drone to anyone considering it!

title: Lightweight but solid
text:
This is my first outside drone. I wanted something lightweight that I could backpack around easily.

I've flown a few times in my back field, and the stability at hovering, flying around, was great. The follow me feature didn't seem to work, it just drifted sideways into a tree, but I want to try that one when I have more open ground. My only other complaint is that the remote doesn't give good feedback for the "GPS ON OR OFF" mode or the slow speed/fast speed mode, and the documentation doesn't indicate what one or two beeps means.

Pictures seems to be decent, and the live video feed is awesome. I have a spare pixel3 phone and a google daydream headset that works great in the VR view.

title: Drone Fun!
text: I like this product because two batteries were included and each battery gives you almost 30-minutes of flying time, much better than most drones.  It also included a second set of blades.  The Amazon ad indicated if I ordered it now, I would get $100 off which DID NOT happen.  The drone company, however, offered me a third battery, additional blades and extended the warranty to compensate.  Also, the distance it can fly was greater than most other drones I looked at.  I wish it had an Obstacle Avoidance feature and the directions were a little more detailed. However, since I am just a beginner and learning, I was able to fly this drone right out of the box without much difficulty.  The remote battery lasts much longer than the drone batteries so it doesn't need to be charged as often.  In wind, this drone does drift a bit when flying but holds its on while hovering.  It takes great pictures and video but I haven't been experimenting much with these since I want to get proficient at flying first.

title: Pairing with phone instructions are terrible

title: Easier to fly than we even thought it would be!
text: My wife and I have wanted an RC craft for many years, but hesitated because we thought it would be too difficult and we didn't have the time to mess with learning.  This year, for our 38th wedding anniversary, we purchased this Ruko F11 Drone. It is amazingly easy to fly and has all kinds of cool features. We have only gone out twice  with it for half hour each time., but already tested most of the features.  It returns to where it launched from, within about 3 meters. It self adjusts when blown by the wind. The video and still camera are easy to use, though aiming the lens is pretty tricky (especially in the wind).  We were not able to get the hand signals to work yet, but that may be due to the wind not allowing a steady image. We have also not tested way points yet.  Much of the manual is pretty cryptic on these extra features.  But, there is good info on the web.

title: Perfect drone for all skill levels.
text:
For my first drone, this is exactly what I need. I‚Äôve been wanting a drone for so long and after waiting and reading and watching reviews I took the plunge. No regrets at all so far. With two batteries that hold for the length of time they‚Äôre rated at, 30 mins. each, I have plenty of time to practice flying skills. If you are as new to drone flying as I am (even with video gaming experience reaching way back) it does have its learning curve. I make sure I‚Äôm away from everything and just fly - the only way to practice. It did come with spare propellers but I also bought a separate set that Amazon recommended. It also comes with two rather short cables for charging either the remote and/or the batteries. Charging time does take a bit so keep that in mind. I had seen somewhere an actual device made to charge two of these at once, but really I just use my own longer cable and 5v adapter and it works just fine like that. It also has a beginner mode that is active by default on the app which is definitely a good idea as this thing can escape from view real fast and unless you are already used to looking at the FPV the drone gives you could do some chasing. Once you want to take the leap though, disabling beginner mode is just a click and then you can set your own limits to the distance, height, and return height for the drone. The max is 2000 m and to be honest as a biginner that is more than far enough. Going any further sounds fun in theory but I‚Äôm more than happy with this as I progress to better flying skills. The case is pretty good quality and the instructions in English are very easy to follow and complete. It also comes with a quick start thicker insert that you can use for reference quickly instead of thumbing through the manual.
Again, I say this is a home run for sure and I could not be more satisfied at all.

title: Great Drone
text: Just bought the Roku f11 pro Drone . I've flown it a couple of times now and I have to say it does everything I was looking for in a drone . Photos and videos are clear and the drone is easy to operate and with a little bit more practice I might possibly get some vr goggles and do alittle bit of racing .

title: Impressive - A+ bang for the buck, maybe best value in drones
text:
Wow. About five flights in and extremely impressed with the engineering, design, but above all the quality. Prior experience was about two weeks with a $100 drone but this device is about 5,000% better and more able than that one.

I don't think you can beat the fun factor + features of this device at this price point. You can pay more but I don't think that you get more in the exchange. So if you want a starter or entry-level quad device - this is IT.

Lots of great features. In order of importance:

(1) Flight time is incredible - nearly an hour in the box (among 2x batteries)
(2) Compared to other drones at this price point this guy is STURDY (high quality)
(3) FUN to fly
(4) Tons of additional features from GPS flight / recovery / 5 gHz connection
(5) USB (micro) rechargeable batteries + controller (I have a ton of these cables lying around)
(6) Folds into a protective foam carrying case the size of a car battery for easy portability

I see a lot of value in the GPS but I actually found it to be not what I was looking for - for backyard flying (close to the house / obstacles) I prefer the "attitude" mode which just means manual / user is in full control.

Out of a 100, I give this baby a 98 - especially, again, at this price point - you're not going to do any better.

I just have two things to mention that could use some improvement - both possible with updated firmware:

(1) Device tends to lose altitude during turns - it is very minor, but if the device pivots / yaws especially in a mid- to high-speed turn, it tends to drop altitude slightly during the maneuever. This is not something that cannot be corrected - I've found myself just giving it a little "boost" with the left joystick while turning - but during turns in tighter space it can be jarring. I think it is because the device is redirecting power to the turn and in doing so it doesn't have as much available, at the inflection point, to keep the device level - it is easily corrected for but I thought that I'd mention it

(2) I'm still getting used to landing - in fact my entire last flight was dedicated to practicing landing. So what happens is if there's any movement due to right joystick corrections meant to keep the device steady in 2D (wind primarily) at all the device tends to not want to land properly, in that it somehow senses the imminent proximity of the ground / surface and "jumps" up while you're trying to get the skids to touch down - I have been tinkering with the one-touch button landing feature and to be honest I have not yet mastered it - compared to other drones it feels finicky when trying to touch down. The workaround could be just using the cut-off which requires about a three-second hold while hovering VERY near the ground but I did this at too high altitude at one point and it dropped a little too suddenly for my taste, so I'm back to the drawing board more or less. My solution while I get used to it is to simply land in grass which is a lot more forgiving than harder surfaces - but I think even on brick / asphault this is something that I'll be able to figure out, in time.

Like I said - 98 out of 100 on this beast. You're not going to find a better one unless you're shelling out 3-10x the price. Job well done by the engineering team.

CFO

title: Excellent Customer Service for a Great Drone
text:
[[VIDEOID:411c59426510e50336dd4dd5e9f17b1d]] I bought this drone initially for the hd video, but there was a significant problem with the initial drone's video quality. Between Amazon and the company's excellent product support, however, I received a replacement drone in no time. This customer service for me is a big deal. The drone video quality is now excellent. I seem a little slow to master this contraption, so it's highly likely this is a 5-star device being operated by a 3-star user. That said, I'll share some of my challenges.

It says it can be operated inside, so I thought this might be a good way to get familiar with the drone's basic operation. I'd follow the instructions for inside takeoff, and just like that it would it careen into something. It doesn't seem to want to just go three feet up and hold still. It prefers to go three feet up and careen wildly to the right or left. After multiple crashes and terrifying the cat, I decided to move outside.

Usually, the outside operation works pretty well. The video I attached, however, shows one instance where my transmitter suddenly lost connection with the drone at precisely the same time it was running it out of power at relatively high altitude. (My iPhone conveniently decided to change wifi from Ruko to my home's wifi network instead.) I retained the "death spiral" down as I was trying to regain control of the thing and (a) keep from crashing and (b) keep from crashing in neighbor's yards.

The remote is not particularly intuitive to use, but I think it just requires practice. The drone's camera is quite good, as mentioned previously, but the final video needs to be edited due to the choppiness that takes place when you change direction or encounter winds. It seems remarkably durable, which is very important for a drone too.

I do recommend this drone for new flyers, but I also recommend getting the extended warranty and being sure you read everything carefully. It's a great product, but it's NOT a toy!

Overall I'm beyond happy with my purchase and if you're looking for a drone to start out with that has a ton of incredible features, GET THIS DRONE! 110% worth the investment!

title: A definite win!!!
text:
*****5 STARS*****
I bought my Ruko drone at the beginning of March. I have had a dozen or so drones and helicopters in the last 12-15 years so I do have quite a bit of flight experience. The Ruko drone is a dream compared to all of them!
I have flown it 3-4 times per week and I still get 30mins of flight time out of each battery. I love this drone. It is super simple to fly! It hovers when you let go of the controls right where it is. It automatically adjusts and keeps itself in the same spot when you let go of the controls.
PROS:
Flight-

Flight time is awesome! 30mins per battery. Stable and easy to fly. I let my daughter who has never flown anything RC and she did it effortlessly.
The distance is adjustable.
Can be flown first person or line of sight.
The speed can be adjusted to three different levels. So if it‚Äôs a tight area you can slow down the movements to help avoid crashing into objects.
It also has a self landing feature that is awesome! Push the button and it will start landing right then. It won‚Äôt just drop either. It slows itself down and lands smooth and gently.
It also has a return to home feature that is cool. Hit the button and it comes back and lands from the spot it took off.
In my opinion the greatest thing about this drone is how stable it flys in the wind. Every single drone I have had up until this one, I could not fly if there was any wind. Not this one! I‚Äôve flown it in some pretty nasty wind(20+mph) with ease!

Camera-
The camera takes great video and pictures. I‚Äôm not a camera pro so I can‚Äôt really get too detailed about the quality. So far it does everything I need it to do.

Battery-
The life of the battery seems to be holding great! I fly my Ruko quite a bit(3-4 times per week for an hour) and have not seen any drop in flight time. The battery‚Äôs are easy to install and remove. Pinch the buttons on the sides and it pops out. Push it back in until it clicks. Simple. Charge time isn‚Äôt bad at all. I haven‚Äôt timed it or anything however, I‚Äôve had drones in the past that take half the day or more to charge one battery. This one is a couple hours.

Durability-
So I am very impressed with how tough this drone is. I have crashed it into my tree(or two) and into my clothes line and have yet to change a blade or repair anything else. It still flys perfect! Not even a cracked or broken blade.

CONS:

Flight-
Be careful when using the return to home feature...if you fly it to where there is a tree or house or any other object between the drone and the spot it took off from, it doesn‚Äôt know that and will crash into them trying to get back to where it left from.
The only other thing that I would like to see improved is the lag between the camera and phone when I am flying. It is pretty good til you get a couple hundred feet away then it starts lagging and the first person view is worthless.
The only other thing I would change is the camera recording sound. You have to manually turn it on each time or you get a silent video. In order to turn it on you have to be paired with your phone. That part sucks.
These are the only cons I have found with this drone.

So to sum it up, this drone is awesome! I definitely recommend it! I have recommended it to friends already.
A buddy of mine is a drone freak! He custom builds his own. He was impressed with my Ruko. He really liked the flight time.
If you want a fun and easy drone to fly, this is a great place to start no matter what level of experience you have flying drones.

Ree B

title: Good First Impressions, Not Hard For A Beginner, Need More Use For A Deeper Review
text:
I recently became interested in buying a drone as a complement to photo/video work I enjoy doing when I go out to different places. I was looking for something at a reasonable price with some decent features, and the Ruko F11 came to my attention as a generally low-cost intro-level drone with some options that go beyond the very basics. A little more digging found the F11 Pro, which comes with a second battery and a few more features for a very similar price to the base version along with buying an extra battery separately, so I went with the Pro and bought a micro-SD card to use in the unit for recording video/photo.

Out of the box, the drone is essentially ready to fly once you do a bit of initial setup. You can install an app that allows you to see through your phone what the drone sees, and the remote has a convenient clip that will hold the phone in place. I took the case off my Galaxy S10+ because it fit a little better without it.

It is very important to go through the full setup process for calibration. If you skip any steps or don't let them complete, you will run the risk of the drone trying to fly off on you as soon as you direct it into the air, and fighting with the controls can be a difficult experience especially for a novice. I had this happen to me twice and the second time, it came close to veering into the side of a hill before I got it close enough to cut the motors for a semi-rough landing, but the drone itself was undamaged and it was a lesson learned. Do not just assume everything is good to go just because you calibrated it in a different place half an hour ago.

That said, setup is relatively easy and the instructions walk you through it step by step, whether with the booklet, a separate card that comes with the drone, or through the phone app. When you've set it up properly and connected to the drone's own wifi, you will be able to see remaining battery power in the drone and the remote, through the app. If you're flying the drone close to you and there are some obstacles such as tree limbs or power lines nearby, you might find it easier to steer it while watching it yourself, but once you're used to flying it further and higher away (and if you turn off Beginner limits in the app), this is where viewing it through the app comes in very handy. This will help with positioning, direction, and so on, and adjusting the camera's angle can be done through the remote as well.

Be aware that there are limitations to the distance in which the wifi signal comes clearly back to the phone, so you can fly beyond that and get a choppy visual image. The range of the remote itself extends beyond this, but as a novice drone pilot this was something I found I had to be aware of. It is also important to keep an eye on your battery's charge. Each one lasts nearly half an hour from a full charge, and when it gets low the lights on the drone will start to turn red and it will try to return to its launch point. If there are obstacles in the way, it is not high-end enough to have a feature such as collision detection, so pay attention to that.

As for flying it, I found it to be easy to control and very responsive to my input. As a first-timer, I went to an open park and just got used to how it flies, and of course I had moments where I jerked it too far one way or another, but it held its position very steadily when I brought it close to a fence by a baseball field, elevated it above it, flew over it, then lowered it and repeated the other way. On my second try, I flew it close by some trees and power lines, and it was responsive with a little bit of adjusting needed to account for a mild breeze. I'm not sure yet how much wind I'd risk sending it up in, though.

The primary reason I got it, and the third time I flew it, was to take it down to Shasta Lake in California to view some places left behind when Shasta Dam was built, such as old roads, bridges, and rail locations that are normally underwater except during drought conditions. The drone performed very well here, and I recorded about 35 minutes worth of video that I split between the two batteries I had. This is where I had a near-miss when I didn't go through the proper calibration steps all the way, but that is a lesson learned. You can see some still images I took from videos I captured.

The drone flew steadily and I while I think I would prefer a non-fisheye lens to the one the F11 Pro comes with, along with a gimbal, which the F11 Pro also does not have, I found the video quality to be adequate for what I paid for. If I want better features, I would need to spend a bit more and Ruko offers a newer version of this drone that has a gimbal with a non-fisheye lens, but based on some reviews I've seen the jury may be out as to which one actually flies better.

Anyway, I've found so far that keeping the lens facing straight ahead gives me better color quality to what I'm seeing, and based on the angle of the drone as it's flying I can still see the majority of what I want to. You do get a little bit of the propellers in the shot, but that's not too bad. The fisheye distortion shows a bit more as you're turning or straightening things out. If you don't like the fisheye effect and want more image stabilization, consider a different model, whether one by Ruko or another manufacturer.

Batteries take a few hours to charge, and there are specs listed as to what kind of power adapter you should use. Basically, a phone charger will do fine and you want to make sure it's about 1-3A. This model comes with a nice little carrying case that can house the drone, one battery, the remote, and the documentation that comes with it. It is recommended to keep the battery disconnected from the drone when you are not using it.

The drone software comes with additional features I have not yet had the chance to explore, such as a 'follow you' function, the ability to circle an object for a 360 view of it, and a point-to-point ability you can 'draw' on a map of the place you're in. These are not important features for me, but they are there for those who want to make use of them. The app will also provide you with a flight record and keep what you recorded, but you can use the micro-SD card to transfer higher-quality videos to your computer later.

I think as a first-time user of a drone, this was a good entry point for me. I've found actually flying it to be easy to pick up as a beginner, and with more experience I will get more steady with it. Do be sure to download an app like 'B4UFLY' to check for any restrictions in the area you live in or go to. I live close enough to a small airport that there are height limitations to be aware of, for example. It has some good features and options for a ~$300 price point, and while you might not get everything you want in a drone for that price, this one gives you a good amount of stuff to try if you want to go beyond just flying it around.

title: Highly Recommended Beginner Quadcopter Drone
text: This was my first Quadcopter experience.  The value is outstanding with excellent features including 5G dual-band wifi, GPS, 4K video and photos.  I originally ordered the F-11, then noted there are two versions, the F11 and F11 PRO.  F11 PRO includes enhanced GPS and 4K video, while the F11 has standard GPS and 4K photos, 1080P video.  It took a bit of research to notice the two version and identify the differences.  F11 Pro camera lens is slightly different with no outside ring and the bottom of the camera module is flat where the lower resolution camera module has a dip toward the front.  Replacement camera modules are available online through other sellers for both versions, however Q/A state that the PRO 4K video camera module is not a compatible swap for the F11 1080P camera module.  I did not order to try to upgrade the camera module, rather I returned the purchase through Amazon and upgraded to the F11 PRO which is about $20 more.  The purchase was refunded as soon as the F11 model was dropped off at the shipper with no issues.  Company return/support/upgrade policy is outstanding.

title: Batteries swell
text:
I just received this drone late last night and set it up today. Being an absolute beginner I read and re-read instructions multiple time before even turned it on. App looks pretty simple and setup took only about 5 minutes before the maiden flight.
Flew it for about 20 minutes and battery still had some juice left. There is definitely a learning curve and I will take my time learning everything with it. My friends were amazed by the features, appearance, controllability and picture quality of the drone.... even considering ordering one.:)
Did my research before purchase and I have no regrets for paying a little extra for this F 11 pro.
Update.... I have been practicing with the drone in close quarters in my backyard. Some breeze and my inexperience caused it to crash into a dense tree. I freaked out but to my surprise no blades broke and the drone were ready to fly 30 seconds later. Then it clipped a pine tree branch and still keeps flying. Seems like a sturdy little beast but hoping this was the last time doing these stunts.

Update March 2022
After a year battery packs started to get tight in the drone body. Now it is nearly impossible to remove the battery without some sort of prying tool. Batteries are visibly swollen and flight time cut to half or less. I will have to keep these batteries away from anything flammable because I afraid they will ignite one day‚Ä¶

title: Live video transmission range is really weak, otherwise a great drone.
text:
My biggest issue with this drone is that the live video transmission (to your smart phone) while flying seems to be limited to about 100-170 meters. This is significantly less than advertised for the drone.

Besides this issue, the drone is actually very high quality and fun to fly. The GPS system works very well. However, I do note that when the battery is low the drone will automatically take off and return to home. This is a good thing, except the drone does not fly to it's "return to home altitude" before flying back home. In other words, if you are not flying in a completely remote area with no obstructions in the air, when the drone hits low battery it will take off and hit into something. This is a flaw in the software I think because when you push "return to home" and the battery is not low, the drone will fly up to it's predetermined return to home altitude and then come back.

title: Expectations exceeded with drone perfect for all levels!
text:
[[VIDEOID:4ed3fcfeaa6c8a1f834f719899a954df]] This drone is perfect for anyone wanting to get into learning how to use these things. The quality is great and it can really take a beating. Ha! As you can see by the video, the jerkiness is all from the user. I am not quite skilled enough to fly this thing smoothly and have crashed it into my house and gotten it stuck in a tree. Just a couple scuffs on the blades and that's it! I was pretty impressed with how well this thing holds up. It's easy to learn, but the hand-eye coordination skills take time to get used to. Practice makes perfect!

I love how you can control it from the remote or your phone. It's easiest to use when you hook the phone to the remote though! That's how I'm beginning to learn to properly fly the drone.

My husband is an aerospace engineer who is specialized in drones. He did all the research and the specs are great for all legal use. Anything illegal would be due to user error (IE: not following the rules).

I bought this drone to document our travels throughout the world and I think this is going to exceed my expectations!

title: Outstanding Drone at an Amazing Price Point
text:
I own a 3DR SOLO, so I stepped into the Ruko having flight experience with other drones. I purchased the Ruko primarily because of its compact storage size and extended flight time (with two batteries included), with the intent of traveling with it. So far this drone hasn't disappointed. While it's setup is a bit more cumbersome than the 3DR, the included video tutorial and quick fly instructions minimize the time required. Once it's ready to fly, it's stable, even in moderate wind, and easy to control. The included additional battery, replacement propellers, and carry case are wonderful additions, certainly at this price point. I've had the drone for only a short while, so I'm unable to offer detailed feedback on the camera and flight modes.

One critique - the introductory video is in Chinese, and there appears to be no option to change the language settings or view subtitles. In addition, the video very clearly indicates the drone camera offers 1080P resolution (numbers in Chinese subtitles are still just numbers), which is of course contrary to the advertised resolution of 4K. I'm hopeful the video is simply dated from a previous model or just incorrect.

title: Good drone for beginner and great customer service.
text:
We got one of these units at work and had a blast. So I decided to get myself one. The unit has great control, great video for the price, and lasts a long time in the air. I never brought it back down going, "man this thing needs more battery". The fact it has two batteries is even better. The drone flies and maneuvers greatly for me and was able to zoom zoom around the back yard once I figured it all out.
One side note is anything that gets in between it and you can hurt the camera signal but other than that it flys very far away and stable. Return to home works flawlessly.

Now to the part about customer service. So I decided to take my drone above the tree line, and that's when I believe the battery lost connection, it might have been loose and not secure at the time. The drone fell from the sky and into a 100-foot tree. It did not come down that night and there was a very bad storm coming. I contacted support on this and within the night I got a response. The next day they asked for my address and told me a replacement will be shipped no other questions asked. This was on Dec 23rd. Today I got the new replacement drone and it works flawlessly. Just do not go over trees or water if you can help it! I would say that is A+ Service.
The old drone eventually fell during the 40+mph wind and rain event, and it stayed in that rain for atleast 10 hours. The battery was about 10 feet away. I let the drone and battery dry out and all works except for the camera no longer pivots. So I would say it is also very durable.

All in all, while not a $1k drone, it works and acts like one to me. I would recommend this drone.

title: Good product, BUT POSSIBLE SCAM included
text:
Very handy and easy to learn. Robust and stable in the air. Nice battery duration. Good consideration for the product having included a carrying case, extra battery and extra blades. Camera quality is excellent, thus stabilization could be better. Remote Control is compact and solid, but a little weak to hold the phone; does a good job but it feels like it‚Äôs going to get loose. In summary it is a good option for beginners, practice or just for fun.
BUT, HERE‚Äôs THE CATCH - POSSIBLE SCAM!
Product comes in with a promo card offering free extra battery in exchange for a review in Amazon and ask for evidence through an email. Next step they ask for a shipping address. Then they indicate the address is not good and suggest to purchase the new battery in Amazon and they will refund. Simply don‚Äôt follow, it is not the standard process. They will just keep asking for personal information.

text: I have never owned a drone and so thrilled about this one!  I waited a week or two before practicing so I could study the manual and learn the functions/controls.  Camera and video are great! The only issue I had was I could not get it to connect to my Galaxy S8+ but looks like others have no issues with the same or similar phone so I'll work on it and find a way to connect. text: I just wanted to reach out to anyone who is thinking about purchasing one of these drones. First off it's well worth the money. You get more than you do with a $150 drone. I'm using a Samsung note 10. In terms of a beginner? We are all beginers aren't we at one point? So if your a beginner than I recommend  this drone. title: Great beginner drone!
text:
I have spent about 3 hours flying this drone since I got it. It only came with 1 battery but the seller sent me another one no questions asked, immediately. The batteries seem like they take overnight to charge, which really limits how much flying you can do a day.

The drone itself performs flawlessly, it's so easy to control and is very responsive. My only complaint is sometimes it's hard to get the phone to connect to it without having to restart everything multiple times, and even in an open field you'll be lucky to get 1000-1200 ft before you lose connection and it turns back. I believe it was advertised as up to 4k and something feet, but being limited by your phone connection ruins any chance of that. I've seen other brands where the phone plugs into the remote so you're only limited by your remote range and not your phone range.

Overall it's been a great device and I plan to keep it for a long time or upgrade to something with a greater range and let my kids take this one over, it's that easy to control.

title: ABSOLUTELY LOVE IT
text: I've purchased those cheap drones on a couple of different occasions in the past. You know the ones that you may find in some big box stores or maybe run across randomly in the mall. The one thing they all had in common were the fact they were trash. They were all destroyed of severely damaged almost right out of the box........that being said this is not the experience I've had with the Roku F11. This is the best drone I have owned and was worth every penny I paid for it. I took it out to a local forest preserve a couple of weeks ago and I was attacked by about 9 young people. I didn't know what to do as they surrounded me. One of them quickly ran up to me and grabbed at the controller yelling that's mine give it here as the rest of the crowd circled. I thought to myself, this is it, it's been a good life! In that same moment my savior arrived seemingly out of nowhere. As she yelled out to all of those young people I felt relief immediately....."Back up.....Give him some space" to my surprise they all responded and did exactly what she had instructed. As it turns out daycare providers really know how to deal with large groups of 4 - 7 year old kids. Long story longer those kids really enjoyed the amateur air show I was able to provide all thanks to my Ruko F11 Gim 2 Drone. I would highly recommend this product as it is solid. I appreciate that it came with two batteries and replacement propellers all in a great case to lug it all around. Great purchase. I hope this review helps you make a good decision for you or a loved one.

title: $300 just flew away!
text: Worked for about 2 weeks then took it up and it went into low voltage return to home but it didn't return home it just flew off!! Used the find drone feature and it said it crashed in a field about 1/2 a mile from take off. We searched over an hour around the area the GPS says the drone was. Nada. Never found! I expect a refund for this failure of a product. Like I said for two weeks every function worked great, then little things that I chalked up to a learning curve but when you calibrate the drone every time to set the home for the return to home function you expect it to be close to that spot! This is unexceptable and I expect to be contacted back by your almost non existent customer service.
